post_text:
Hi Walden families!

We hope your summer is going well! With guidance from the state, we are preparing for the reopening of school this fall. Plans and options will be available to you before the end of this month.

We realize that wearing masks may be part of the new reality. If so, what could be better than wearing a mask designed by one of our own students? We invite students to tap into their creative genius and design a mask for Walden. Please send ideas to Hannah, Sharon or Lois by Friday, July 10th. A panel of teachers will be the judges and a local company will print the winning designs on masks to be ready for the first day of school.

There is a template you can use attached. We can't wait to see what you come up with!

Stay safe!
Hannah
Sharon
Lois

post_text:
March 23rd, 2020

Dear Walden Community,

On March 13th, our governor issued a soft closure (dismissal) of schools for two weeks. This afternoon, we received an update letting us know that schools in Utah will remain in this state of soft closure through May 1, 2020. State officials will continue to monitor the current health crisis and make adjustments to the timeline for reopening schools as needed.

We have been amazed at the outpouring of care and support from our Walden families as we figure out how to best educate our students from a distance. There have certainly been plenty of technological glitches and communication hurdles and we realize the great challenge a continued dismissal creates for many of our Walden families. Please know that your physical and mental wellbeing is our primary concern.

Thank you for your continued effort in keeping Walden a safe, patient and strong community. Please stay safe, and healthy.

With warmest regards,
Walden Administration

post_text:
Starting next Tuesday is a wonderful opportunity which we would love our Walden families to attend!

Families Talking Together is an evidence-based program offered through our partnerships with the Boys and Girls Clubs of Utah County and Centro Hispano. It consists of two two-hour sessions focused on helping families talk to their children about various issues such as: teen decision-making, parental concerns, quality relationships, boundary-setting, and discussing difficult topics with your teen. It is designed to be attended by teens and/or parents.

Abraham Hernandez, the Health Promotion Coordinator for Centro Hispano, will be offering this class at Walden on Tuesday, March 3rd and Tuesday, March 10th from 4:00-6:00pm.

Please reach out to us ASAP if you are interested in attending, and we will reserve your spot!

Hi Students & Parents!

For clarification we wanted to send a couple of reminders about the dance tonight, especially if your student is planning on bringing a guest.

-This is a high school dance intended for high school students ages 14-18.
-If you are bringing a guest, you MUST have the signed dance permission form to get in (must have parent signatures).
-Your guest will not be permitted without a filled out and signed form.
-If you are bringing a guest from another school, they should bring a photo ID (school ID is fine).
-If your guest is 18, I need their name right away. We are required to run background checks on all visitors who are 18.

Please let me know if you have questions :) See you tonight!

post_text:
2 HOUR LATE START MONDAY FEBRUARY 3RD

The weather forecast for tonight and tomorrow is predicting lots of snow overnight and in the morning.

We are announcing a 2 HOUR LATE START for Walden on Monday February 3, 2020. If we need to change plans to a full day cancelation, we will make that decision at 7:00 a.m. and get the information out immediately. For 2 hour late start, school will begin at exactly 10:30am. There will be NO morning or afternoon kindergarten, preschool, or other midday programs.

We are making this call early to allow families and staff enough time to make plans with as much notice as possible. If you are concerned about your student's ability to commute safely to school, please use your discretion if you feel it is necessary to keep them home. Thank you and we will update you in the morning via phone call, text and email.

Walden employees and staff should arrive to work as early as they can safely do so. If any employee will be later than 10:00am, or does not feel safe commuting to work, please contact your direct supervisor and work with them.

Dear Walden Families,

Service day was a great success! Not only were we able to reach our goal of $3000 for Sub4Santa, we were able to spend the day with the High School Students carrying out various acts of kindness and service. We are so incredibly proud and grateful for our Walden community of students, parents and teachers! Thank you SO much to everyone who donated, served and supported us during this amazing time. We hope you have a restful and wonderful break! You all deserve it!

Pictured below is a thank you note from one of the Sub4Santa families and the various service activities carried out by Walden HS including:

-Caroling at Specialty Hospital
-Cookies and positive notes at Encircle Youth House
-Community Action Service Food Bank
-Food Drive
-Shopping for Sub 4 Santa
-Blankets for refugees
-Hats for NICU
-Cards for inmates
-Animal Shelter

PS we are up to $1,500 in donations for the Walden Bus, thank you!!!

Comcast Cares Day is TOMORROW! Please come help clean and beautify our school. Comcast donates to Walden per volunteer who shows up so the more the better! It allows us to do exciting things for your students and our facilities. All volunteers will receive a free breakfast, lunch, t-shirt and the happy glow that service brings to the soul.

Please pre-register here: https://www.comcastinthecommunity.com/ even if you are unsure you will be able to attend. And remember, this counts towards your volunteer hours, helps make the school a cleaner, nicer, safer place for our students and for every volunteer who attends, Comcast will donate money to Walden.

post_text:
ART SHOW SUBMISSIONS DUE MONDAY! Please encourage your students to submit their projects. Submitted artworks must also include the official form, available in the art room at both buildings.

This year Walden is hosting an Inspirations Art Show, which will be different than the past Progressions Art Contest. The theme is, "Respect Mother Earth". This is an opportunity for all ages to create 2D, 3D, Photography, Literature and Performing Art that inspire all in their interpretation of what respecting Mother Earth means to them.

The art show will be Thursday, Friday and Saturday April 26-28. The gallery will be up for all to enjoy during the production of Wizard of Oz.

Selected works of art will be chosen to be featured in community venues after the show.

Each artist will be entered into a drawing to win studio time at the Neighborhood Art Center in Provo.

post_text: We are SO proud of our Walden students and families! Today we were awarded with a $22,815 check from Comcast for the volunteer work we did last April. This money goes towards our beautiful new amphitheater, outdoor drinking fountains, steps up the hillside and so many more awesome projects made possible by Comcast's generosity and our AMAZING Walden families and volunteers. We had over 1,100 volunteers, more than any Comcast Cares project in the state of Utah! #ComcastCares

WALKABOUT COMING HOME TONIGHT

Hello high school parents, due to lightning warnings we will be coming home tonight. We need volunteer drivers with 4 wheel or all wheel drive to meet at the school at 6:05pm to follow one of our faculty members up the mountain to the campsite and bring students back to the school for parental pick up. Once students are at the school they will call parents for individual pick up. Please comment below if you can drive to the campsite and will be at the school at 6:05. Thank you for your cooperation!

post_text:
*WALKABOUT UPDATE FOR HIGH SCHOOL PARENTS*
If your child is not on Walkabout please disregard the following.

Due to storm clouds we decided not to take any students up Timpanogos mountain today. All of our students who attended walkabout went on the Rock Canyon hike and are staying on camp grounds between the Rock Canyon trailhead and Squaw Peak. We are keeping an eye on the weather as there is still a slight risk of showers in that area and we know that soggy students are sad students. Please keep an eye on your email or our Facebook page for updates in case we need to bring the students home quickly.

Thank you!
